    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\r\n![2023-11-04_23-23-13_echo](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/61395246/88e82512-c4eb-4c9e-bfe1-47b337390696)\r\n![2023-11-04_23-25-34_lua](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/61395246/b0385291-5d55-4d34-b9b4-513358432a72)\r\n![2023-11-04_23-25-57_reg](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/61395246/2c10d4d3-0ba9-4d33-bc82-da397f2261fb)\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n### Expected behavior\r\n\r\nIt would be a nice qol and cosmetic feature to have syntax highlighting in `cmdline` just like [Noice](https://github.com/folke/noice.nvim#-features) has.\r\n\r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/61395246/e57f824b-02be-4050-b7e5-78c9c9dca1a6)\r\n![image](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/61395246/c64ded0c-03cf-4bcf-959e-29b9388da5c4)\r\n\r\n\r\nIt looks like the `cmdline` is capable of showing highlighted text ( as shown in the screenshot below where the `=` register has highlighting ).\r\n\r\n![2023-11-04_22-23-19_highl](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/assets/61395246/d90b43c1-d051-477b-9dfc-7cfd5f4507c4)\r\n",
    "closed_at": "2023-12-03T15:14:17Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "> where the `=` register has highlighting\r\n\r\nThat's driven by nvim_parse_expression https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/7ce36b7997bf04b6fafdfec482b1a29629b49bd8/src/nvim/api/vimscript.c#L438\r\n\r\nbut that doesn't help for cmdline Ex commands, which are not expressions.\r\n\r\nInstead we would want to highlight the cmdline using normal treesitter-based syntax highlighting, perhaps using an internal scratch buffer.",
